.6439579129219055, "span": {"begin": 1006, "end": 1019}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7040"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TGF-&beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9959384799003601, "span": {"begin": 1049, "end": 1058}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-6", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9727333188056946, "span": {"begin": 1087, "end": 1091}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:59067"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-21", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9718836545944214, "span": {"begin": 1095, "end": 1100}}, {"id": ["CL:0000815"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Treg", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.806893527507782, "span": {"begin": 1179, "end": 1183}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Th17", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.6977720856666565, "span": {"begin": 1250, "end": 1254}}, {"id": ["CL:0000815"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Treg", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8714301586151123, "span": {"begin": 1259, "end": 1263}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7040"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TGF-&beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9952777028083801, "span": {"begin": 1272, "end": 1281}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-6", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9812182784080505, "span": {"begin": 1354, "end": 1358}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "immune cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7274761199951172, "span": {"begin": 1368, "end": 1380}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Th17 phenotype", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.6654072403907776, "span": {"begin": 1433, "end": 1447}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999867677688599, "span": {"begin": 1453, "end": 1459}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001327", "mim:109100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "autoimmune diseases", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999648928642273, "span": {"begin": 1466, "end": 1485}}, {"id": ["CL:0000815"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Treg", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6793658137321472, "span": {"begin": 1572, "end": 1576}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999918937683105, "span": {"begin": 1615, "end": 1620}}], "text": "The ratio between Th17 and T regulatory (Treg) cells is essential for maintaining a balanced immune environment (Noack and Miossec, 2014; Fasching et al., 2017; Lee, 2018). Both cells are derived from CD4+ lymphocytes, a subset of T lymphocytes.  On one hand, the role of Treg is to dampen the immune response by tempering the activity of CTLs, also called CD8+ cytotoxic T cells. Tregs are induced by TGF-&beta; and FoxP3 (Forkhead box P3), which plays a major role in the activation from the na&iuml;ve state to the activated Treg state. Consequently, the expression of FoxP3 well reflects the Treg activity (Fontenot et al., 2003); they are also characterized by a high expression of CD25 (Interleukin 2 receptor -chain). To highlight their immunosuppressive role in the TME, their elimination has been shown to lead to tumor immunity (Shimizu et al., 1999).  On the other hand, the role of Th17 cells is to enhance the immune response by producing pro-inflammatory signals like IL-17, IL-22, or IL-23. Naive T cells are also activated partly by TGF-&beta;, but a co-stimulation with IL-6 or IL-21 is necessary; indeed, the absence of these proinflammatory cytokines leads to Treg differentiation instead (Bettelli et al., 2006).   In short, both Th17 and Treg require TGF-&beta; to be activated; however, in a stressed environment, the production of IL-6 by other immune cells leads to a preferential differentiation towards the Th17 phenotype.  In cancer or in autoimmune diseases, this balance between the two phenotypes is disturbed &nbsp;with a higher presence of Treg and leads to adverse outcomes such as tumor maintenance (Lin et al., 2019; He et al., 2020; Yan et al., 2020).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 22:02:05 +0000 2026"}